## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified disposal today is understanding that "delete" in a cloud environment is not a single action — it is a process that must account for every location where data may exist, including locations that are not immediately obvious.

In a cloud environment like AWS, ePHI from the OpenMRS deployment may exist in: the primary RDS database instance, automated RDS snapshots, manual RDS snapshots created for testing or backup purposes, the weekly S3 export files in the backup bucket, CloudWatch log streams containing patient MRNs from the OpenMRS audit log, EC2 EBS volumes (the root volume and any data volumes), EC2 AMI images created from the OpenMRS instance, S3 object versions and delete markers if versioning is enabled, AWS Backup recovery points if AWS Backup was used, any data shared with assessment evidence (screenshots that may include patient data), and potentially in CloudTrail logs if API calls included patient identifiers in their parameters.

None of these locations will be automatically cleared by terminating the EC2 instance or deleting the RDS instance. Each requires a specific disposal action. The disposal checklist is not a courtesy — it is the mechanism that ensures no ePHI remains in an uncontrolled location after the system is decommissioned.

This is why NIST SP 800-88 distinguishes between Clear (overwriting accessible storage), Purge (rendering data unrecoverable against laboratory-level attacks), and Destroy (physically destroying the media) — different disposal contexts require different sanitization rigor. For cloud-hosted systems where MyClinic does not own the physical media, the primary mechanism is cryptographic erasure: destroying the encryption keys that protect the data renders the encrypted data permanently unreadable even if the physical storage is later recovered or repurposed by AWS.

