## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The sequencing discipline — archive verification before destruction, and cryptographic erasure as defense-in-depth — was shaped by reflecting on the **Advocate Medical Group breach of 2013**, which resulted in a $5.55 million HIPAA settlement. The breach involved unencrypted laptops containing patient data stolen from an employee's car.

What made the Advocate case significant for disposal thinking: the data on those laptops was never formally inventoried or tracked as part of a data management program. Patient data had accumulated on devices that were not subject to the same controls as the primary clinical systems — a disposal and data management gap that made the breach possible.

The cloud equivalent of the Advocate scenario is ePHI accumulating in unexpected AWS locations — CloudWatch logs with patient MRNs, EC2 AMI images captured for testing, S3 object versions not covered by the primary backup policy. The comprehensive disposal checklist that works through every AWS service where ePHI may exist is the technical response to the Advocate pattern: systematic inventory of all data locations before disposal begins, not a best-effort cleanup that misses the non-obvious locations.

