## What I Am Still Thinking About

The patient record archive — retained in Glacier Deep Archive for 7 years with the KMS key preserved — creates a long-term data stewardship obligation that extends years beyond the system's operational life.

Who is responsible for that archive? The ISSO who executed the disposal may not be at MyClinic in 7 years. The KMS key must be accessible when records need to be retrieved (for patient requests, legal proceedings, or audits). The archive must be monitored to confirm the data remains intact and the encryption key remains valid.

This is an under-discussed aspect of healthcare data governance: the disposition of clinical records at the end of a system's life requires a formal data stewardship plan that names responsible parties and establishes monitoring procedures for the retention period. The Compliance Officer should own this plan, not the ISSO — the obligation is clinical and regulatory, not technical.

I want to add a formal data stewardship designation to the disposal report: a named individual (or organizational role) responsible for the archive for the duration of the retention period, with documented procedures for record retrieval requests and an annual confirmation that the archive remains intact and accessible.

